## Overview

**Express.js**, or simply **Express**, is a back-end web application framework for building [[REST API]]s with [[Node.js]]. It has been called the de facto standard server framework for Node.js. It is designed for building web applications and APIs and is the backend component of popular development stacks like the MEAN, MERN, and MEVN stacks.

## History

Express was created by TJ Holowaychuk and first released in 2010. It was inspired by the Sinatra framework for Ruby. In June 2014, the rights to manage the project were acquired by StrongLoop, which was later acquired by IBM in September 2015. The project is now maintained by the Node.js Foundation.

## Key Features

### Routing

Express provides a robust routing mechanism. Routes are defined using HTTP methods and URL patterns:

```
app.get('/api/users', (req, res) => {
  res.json({ users: [] });
});

app.post('/api/users', (req, res) => {
  // Create a new user
});
```

### Middleware

Middleware functions have access to the request object, the response object, and the next middleware function. They can execute code, modify request/response objects, end the request-response cycle, or call the next middleware.

```
app.use((req, res, next) => {
  console.log(`${req.method} ${req.url}`);
  next();
});
```

### Template Engines

Express supports various template engines like Pug, EJS, and Handlebars for server-side rendering of HTML pages.

### Static Files

Express can serve static files (images, CSS, [[JavaScript]]) using the built-in `express.static` middleware.

## Getting Started

```
# Create a new project
mkdir my-api && cd my-api
npm init -y
npm install express
```

Create a basic server:

```
const express = require('express');
const app = express();

app.get('/', (req, res) => {
  res.send('Hello World!');
});

app.listen(3000, () => {
  console.log('Server running on port 3000');
});
```

## Related Technologies

- **[[Node.js]]** — The runtime Express is built on
- **[[REST API]]** — The architecture Express is commonly used to implement
- **[[React]]** — Frontend library often served by Express backends
- **[[Web Development]]** — Express is a core backend tool in web dev
